  "prompt": "How much of demonetized money, might not come back to the banking system?",
  "response": "The exact amount of demonetized currency that might not return to the banking system can vary depending on the context and the specific demonetization event being referred to. However, I can provide some general insights based on historical examples, particularly India's demonetization in 2016.\n\n### **India's Demonetization (2016)**\nIn November 2016, the Indian government demonetized \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 currency notes, which accounted for about 86% of the total currency in circulation at the time. The goal was to curb black money, counterfeit currency, and promote digital transactions. \n\n- **Total Demonetized Currency**: Approximately \u20b915.44 lakh crore (\u20b915.44 trillion).\n- **Currency Returned to Banks**: Around \u20b915.28 lakh crore (99% of the demonetized currency) was deposited back into the banking system.\n- **Currency Not Returned**: About \u20b916,000 crore (roughly 1% of the demonetized currency) was estimated to have not returned to the banking system.\n\n### **Reasons for Currency Not Returning**\n1. **Black Money**: Some individuals with unaccounted wealth may have chosen not to deposit their cash to avoid scrutiny or taxation.\n2. **Counterfeit Currency**: Fake notes could not be deposited and thus were effectively destroyed.\n3. **Lost or Destroyed Currency**: Some notes might have been lost, damaged, or destroyed and were never returned to the system.\n4. **Hoarding**: Individuals or entities may have chosen to hold onto cash for various reasons, including distrust of the banking system.\n\n### **General Observations**\nIn most demonetization events, the majority of the demonetized currency tends to return to the banking system. The portion that does not return is often relatively small, typically ranging from 1% to 5%, depending on the effectiveness of the policy and the extent of the informal economy.\n\n### **Conclusion**\nIn the case of India's 2016 demonetization, about **1% of the demonetized currency** did not return to the banking system. Similar outcomes can be expected in other contexts, though the exact percentage can vary based on specific economic and policy conditions.",
